    {
      "id": "/page/0/Text/9",
      "block_type": "Text",
      "html": "<p block-type=\"Text\">The number of assets in Mountain Range options generally ranges from a low of 4 or 5 to a high of about 20. Owing to their complex payoff and path dependency, idiosyncratic characteristics of each asset need to be taken into account. Hence one cannot assume homogeneity of assets for either small or large baskets, making any closed-form approximation (especially in light of path dependence) intractable. As a result, Mountain Range options, specially the path-dependent varieties such as the Himalayan, are calculated using Monte Carlo simulation [1]. In light of their high-dimensional payoffs due to large number of assets and time points, to speed up convergence, specially for first- and second-order Greeks, usually one or more variance-reduction techniques are employed.</p>",
      "page": 312,
      "polygon": [
        [
          303.1199951171875,
          255.505859375
        ],
        [
          515.3984375,
          255.505859375
        ],
        [
          515.3984375,
          449.34490966796875
        ],
        [
          303.1199951171875,
          449.34490966796875
        ]
      ],
