    {
      "id": "/page/0/Text/10",
      "block_type": "Text",
      "html": "<p block-type=\"Text\" class=\"has-continuation\">The other challenge posed by these options is the correlation. Even in simple lognormal models, the sheer size of the correlation matrix can become a challenge. Since for <i>n</i> assets there can be <i>n(n</i> âˆ’ 1<i>)/</i>2 distinct correlations, even for a modest basket of 10 assets, 45 distinct correlations are possible. Moreover, obtaining the pairwise correlations themselves is not straightforward. If, theoretically speaking, there existed <i>n(n</i> âˆ’ 1<i>)/</i>2 traded spread options on each pair, their implied correlations could be used with the spread options as hedges. However, it is unlikely that every pair of assets in a basket would have a traded spread option. Even if they did, their sheer number would make transaction costs prohibitive, even for moderate bidâ€“ask spreads. Hence historical correlations are more often used, even though as with all historical estimates, they are hard to hedge</p>",
      "page": 312,
      "polygon": [
