    {
      "id": "/page/1/Text/5",
      "block_type": "Text",
      "html": "<p block-type=\"Text\">performing asset would in most scenarios leave the worse performing assets, and since no asset is given a chance to growâ€”it would get removed in the next cutâ€”we are left with increasingly worse performing assets. Thus greediness would actually be a bad strategy compared to some predetermined asset-removal order. Increasing volatility increases this dispersion, further reducing the payoff of the Himalayan. We remind the reader that this simple analysis applies to a homogeneous basket. Individual volatilities, dividends, and a nonconstant correlation can affect the payoff in ways not always easily explained.</p>",
